EKS Project Run Steps (Terraform)
📁 1. Clone the repository
git clone https://github.com/harathi-mutyam/PRODUCTION-EKS.git
cd PRODUCTION-EKS
📂 2. Go to Terraform working directory

Based on your instructions:

cd eks-project/terraform/eks

👉 Make sure this folder contains:

main.tf
eks.tf
vpc.tf
provider.tf
dev.tfvars
☁️ 3. Configure AWS CLI (mandatory)
aws configure

Set:

AWS Access Key
Secret Key
Region → us-east-1
🪣 4. Create S3 backend bucket (if not already created)

If your backend.tf uses S3:

aws s3 mb s3://your-terraform-state-bucket --region us-east-1

👉 Also ensure DynamoDB table exists if state locking is used.

🔑 5. Create EC2 Key Pair (VERY IMPORTANT)

Your project uses:

data "aws_key_pair"

So key MUST already exist in AWS.

Step 1: Create local key
ssh-keygen -t rsa -b 4096 -f ~/.ssh/ec2_keypair
Step 2: Import into AWS
aws ec2 import-key-pair \
  --key-name ec2_keypair \
  --public-key-material fileb://~/.ssh/ec2_keypair.pub \
  --region us-east-1
Step 3: Verify
aws ec2 describe-key-pairs --key-names ec2_keypair
⚙️ 6. Initialize Terraform
terraform init

👉 This will:

download AWS provider
initialize backend (S3)
prepare modules
🔍 7. Validate configuration
terraform validate
📊 8. Plan infrastructure
terraform plan -var-file="dev.tfvars"

Check carefully:

VPC creation
EKS cluster
Node groups
EC2 bastion
IAM roles
🚀 9. Apply infrastructure
terraform apply -var-file="dev.tfvars"

Type:

yes

Post Deployment (Bastion Host Access)

Because cluster is private:

SSH into Bastion
ssh -i ~/.ssh/ec2_keypair ubuntu@<bastion-public-ip>
Configure Kubernetes access
aws configure
aws eks update-kubeconfig --region us-east-1 --name eks-demo

Verify:

kubectl get nodes
13. Install Helm (inside bastion)
curl -fsSL -o get_helm.sh https://raw.githubusercontent.com/helm/helm/main/scripts/get-helm-3
chmod 700 get_helm.sh
./get_helm.sh
14. Install AWS Load Balancer Controller
helm repo add eks https://aws.github.io/eks-charts
helm repo update

Install:

helm install aws-load-balancer-controller eks/aws-load-balancer-controller \
  -n kube-system \
  --set clusterName=eks-demo \
  --set region=us-east-1 \
  --set vpcId=<vpc-id> \
  --set serviceAccount.annotations."eks\.amazonaws\.com/role-arn"=<IAM-role>

Verify:

kubectl get deployment -n kube-system

15. Deploy Microservices
kubectl apply -f ns.yaml
kubectl apply -f product.yaml
kubectl apply -f cart.yaml
kubectl apply -f payments.yaml
16. Ingress Deployment (HTTP ALB)
kubectl apply -f ingress.yaml

ALB will be automatically created.

 17. Enable TLS (HTTPS Setup)
Step 1: Create Route53 Hosted Zone
example.com
Step 2: Create ACM Certificate

Request certificate for:

cart.example.com
product.example.com
payments.example.com
Step 3: Update Ingress

Add:

alb.ingress.kubernetes.io/listen-ports: '[{"HTTPS": 443}, {"HTTP": 80}]'
alb.ingress.kubernetes.io/certificate-arn: <cert-arn>
alb.ingress.kubernetes.io/ssl-redirect: '443'

Apply:

kubectl apply -f ingress.yaml

18. Host-Based Routing (Production)
Domain	Service
cart.example.com	Cart
product.example.com	Product
payments.example.com	Payments

19. Destroy Infrastructure (Cleanup)
terraform destroy -var-file="dev.tfvars"




